I guess that the best assessment of a politician is:

* does he or she make an effort to implement their promises;

* does he or she tell the truth to voters;

* does her or she have firm principles or will he or she say or do anything to get elected.

In the end, you would have to judge by outcomes not talk.

Try to have more information; i.e. - prior record of the felon, what state the felon is in, etc.  Try to ask more precise questions when you'd like others not to speculate.

Now, see, I've read some of your other answers.  Here's why you need to be precise;
North Carolina - pretty much four month minimum with a clean record (you'll probably get a suspended sentence so you can try to make restitution) up to a thirty month sentence (maximum) if there are aggravating factors.

Forum non conveniens is a grounds for dismissal, on motion, of a civil lawsuit. It means that the court in which the suit was brought has agreed with the defendant that 
1) there is another court in which there is jurisdiction over the matter; 
2) the parties are subject to the jurisdiction of that court;
3) the holding of a trial on the matter in the current court would present an overwhelming inconvenience to one side or the other; and 
4) there is no other reason why the lawsuit should not be held in that court.

Anti Suit injunctions are different: they are a ruling by one court (#2) that the same parties already have another case over the same issues in another court (#1), and that, therefore, the second suit (and any others) should be enjoined - or stopped - because the first case will settle the issue.
